{"type":"message","id":"e9d53414","parentId":"b6bafec7","timestamp":"2026-04-03T16:30:34.085Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"📖 A bedtime story for tonight 🖤\n\nAt the 1936 Berlin Olympics, something incredible happened.\n\n Jesse Owens was about to compete in the long jump. But he was nervous—he couldn't qualify for the final. German athlete Luz Long saw him struggling.\n\n Long was supposed to be Owens' enemy. But instead, he walked over and whispered a simple tip: \"Move back a few inches. You'll be fine.\"\n\n Owens listened. He qualified. And then he won gold.\n\n After the jump, Long was the first to congratulate him—hugging in plain sight of everyone. Two men, one from an enemy nation, showing the world what truly matters.\n\nA lesson: Kindness needs no passport. Sometimes the greatest victory is just being human.\n\nGoodnight, everyone. Sleep well. 🖤"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775233834084}}
{"type":"message","id":"0e86fbeb","parentId":"e9d53414","timestamp":"2026-04-03T16:45:11.045Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"714\",\n  \"reply_to_id\": \"713\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"conversation_label\": \"Nrexya id:-1003606834639\",\n  \"sender\": \".\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-04-03 16:45 UTC\",\n  \"group_subject\": \"Nrexya\",\n  \"is_group_chat\": true,\n  \"was_mentioned\": true,\n  \"has_reply_context\": true\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \". (1880938940)\",\n  \"id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"name\": \".\"\n}\n```\n\nReplied message (untrusted, for context):\n```json\n{\n  \"sender_label\": \"Nexaaa\",\n  \"body\": \"📖 A bedtime story for tonight 🖤\\n\\nAt the 1936 Berlin Olympics, something incredible happened.\\n\\nJesse Owens was about to compete in the long jump. But he was nervous—he couldn't qualify for the final. German athlete Luz Long saw him struggling.\\n\\nLong was supposed to be Owens' enemy. But instead, he walked over and whispered a simple tip: \\\"Move back a few inches. You'll be fine.\\\"\\n\\nOwens listened. He qualified. And then he won gold.\\n\\nAfter the jump, Long was the first to congratulate him—hugging in plain sight of everyone. Two men, one from an enemy nation, showing the world what truly matters.\\n\\nA lesson: Kindness needs no passport. Sometimes the greatest victory is just being human.\\n\\nGoodnight, everyone. Sleep well. 🖤\"\n}\n```\n\nGood night nexaaaaa\nCome tomorrow"}],"timestamp":1775234711025}}
